### Generics in C#

Generics allow you to define type-safe data structures and methods without committing to a specific data type.

### Why Generics?

Without generics, you would need to use `object` type with boxing/unboxing:

```csharp
// Without generics (non-generic ArrayList)
ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
list.Add(123);       // Boxing
int x = (int)list[0];  // Unboxing, no type safety

// With generics (List<T>)
List<int> list = new List<int>();
list.Add(123);       // No boxing
int x = list[0];     // No unboxing, type safe
```

### Generic Benefits

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Type safety | Compile-time type checking |
| Performance | No boxing/unboxing for value types |
| Code reuse | Single implementation for all types |
| Readability | Clear intent in code |

### Generic Constraints

```csharp
public class Repository<T> where T : class
{
    public void Save(T item) { }
}

// Constraint types
public class Example<T> where T : struct        // Value type
public class Example<T> where T : class         // Reference type
public class Example<T> where T : new()         // Parameterless constructor
public class Example<T> where T : SomeClass    // Derives from SomeClass
public class Example<T> where T : ISomeInterface  // Implements interface
public class Example<T, U> where T : U          // Type argument constraint
```

### Multiple Constraints

```csharp
public class DataStore<T> where T : class, IComparable<T>, new()
{
    public T Create() => new T();
    public int Compare(T a, T b) => a.CompareTo(b);
}
```

### Default Keyword

```csharp
public T GetDefault<T>()
{
    return default(T);  // null for reference, 0 for numeric, false for bool
}
```

### Generic Interfaces

```csharp
public interface IRepository<T>
{
    T GetById(int id);
    void Save(T item);
    void Delete(int id);
}

public class UserRepository : IRepository<User>
{
    public User GetById(int id) => /* ... */;
    public void Save(User user) => /* ... */;
    public void Delete(int id) => /* ... */;
}
```

### Generic Delegates

```csharp
public delegate T Transformer<T>(T input);

Transformer<int> square = x => x * x;
int result = square(5);  // 25
```

> **Key Point:** Generics provide type safety without performance overhead. Use constraints to specify what capabilities the type parameter must support. The `default` keyword returns the default value for any type. Generics work with classes, methods, interfaces, delegates, and structs.

### Covariance and Contravariance

```csharp
IEnumerable<object> objs = new List<string>();  // Covariance (out T)
Action<string> strAction = (Action<object> obj) => { };  // Contravariance (in T)
```

### Generic Type Inference

```csharp
void Process<T>(T item) { }
Process("hello");  // T inferred as string
```

